    <a title="Clar" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/44794733-clar"><img alt="Clar" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2176576120?book_show_action=true">Nov 19, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Clar" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Clar" href="/user/show/44794733-clar">Clar</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/44794733-clar?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/44794733-clar?shelf=science-fiction">science-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2176576120" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9781566129355783915">An ambitious novel that falls short when it comes to delivering a connection to the characters. Although a case can be made for the protagonist, the concept of empathizing and even considering the secondary characters relevant is not possible. For example, Jenny is never developed to the point where we as readers get to care about her and understand her impact on the main character —it is more about lust than love.<br/><br/>Similarly, the dialogue becomes awkward as it drags on in an non-organic manner. M</span>
  <span id="freeText9781566129355783915" style="display:none">An ambitious novel that falls short when it comes to delivering a connection to the characters. Although a case can be made for the protagonist, the concept of empathizing and even considering the secondary characters relevant is not possible. For example, Jenny is never developed to the point where we as readers get to care about her and understand her impact on the main character —it is more about lust than love.<br /><br />Similarly, the dialogue becomes awkward as it drags on in an non-organic manner. Most of the time, it feels like you are reading essays rather than natural dialogue. The way most characters talk is similar, and no one has a clear voice that stands out.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9781566129355783915" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
